gomodel:SYNGO_400  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: It is demonstrated that RIM1 is required to maintain the structural integrity of the active zone. Genetic removal of active zone proteins RIM1, RIM2, ELKS1 and ELKS2 leads to a loss of Bassoon, Munc13 and Piccolo, and a reduction of RIMBP2 and Cav2.1 (Figure 1), thus showing a severe reduction of the active zone.\n\nIn line with disruption of the active zone, multiple essential functions of the presynaptic terminal are affected, including vesicle docking (figure 2), vesicle priming (figure 7), spontaneous and action potential induced fusion (figure 3 and 5) and calcium influx (figure 4).\n\nRemoval of RIM1/2 or ELKS1/2 alone is not sufficient to disrupt the active zone (figure 7).\n\n10/4/2017 Pim\n- I have added the link to SynGO ID #60 that shows that RIM1 is itself localized to the AZ. I think this strengthens the selected term.. Experimental description: The quadruple homozygote floxed mice for RIM1αβ, RIM2αβγ, ELKS1α, and ELKS2α were generated by crossing single conditional knockout mice (Kaeser et al., 2008; Kaeser et al., 2009; Kaeser et al., 2011 ; Liu et al., 2014)." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7620-2704" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1558-1958" ;
        dc:date           "2018-06-07" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_MF_400" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

